1
00:00:02,760 --> 00:00:05,686
We said before that it’s generally agreed

2
00:00:05,711 --> 00:00:09,603
that the greenhouse effect of a doubling of atmospheric CO2

3
00:00:09,628 --> 00:00:13,709
means the temperature rises about 1.1 degrees Celsius.

4
00:00:13,734 --> 00:00:20,196
So at the current rates it’ll take about 200 years to double the CO2 concentration

5
00:00:20,221 --> 00:00:24,756
resulting in another 1.1 degrees. So, what’s the big deal?

6
00:00:24,780 --> 00:00:29,211
The big deal is because climate models include positive feedback, or amplification,

7
00:00:29,416 --> 00:00:33,180
mostly from increased water vapor as a result of warming oceans.

8
00:00:33,205 --> 00:00:38,256
The idea is that for the 1.1 degree of warming caused by a CO2 increase alone

9
00:00:38,281 --> 00:00:41,238
the ECS, or Equilibrium Climate Sensitivity,

10
00:00:41,263 --> 00:00:45,570
would result in a total increase of between 1.5 and 4.5 degrees.

11
00:00:45,595 --> 00:00:46,343
Okay.

12
00:00:46,368 --> 00:00:49,440
Okay, so how do the climate models compare with the observations?

13
00:00:51,360 --> 00:00:54,443
Predicting future temperature is difficult.

14
00:00:54,468 --> 00:00:57,950
Even the IPCC noted in 2001,

15
00:00:58,800 --> 00:01:03,096
“The climate system is a coupled non-linear chaotic system,

16
00:01:03,120 --> 00:01:08,729
and therefore the long-term prediction of future climate states is not possible.”

17
00:01:08,754 --> 00:01:11,179
Ah, yeah, but they went ahead anyway.

18
00:01:11,204 --> 00:01:14,195
Using over a hundred different models.

19
00:01:14,220 --> 00:01:16,968
So if the science is settled, as we often hear,

20
00:01:16,993 --> 00:01:18,154
all you need is one.

21
00:01:18,179 --> 00:01:19,816
Yeah that should do it.

22
00:01:19,841 --> 00:01:21,468
The one based on science.

23
00:01:21,493 --> 00:01:24,628
This graph shows the many predictions from 102 models.

24
00:01:24,653 --> 00:01:26,995
The black line represents the average.

25
00:01:27,020 --> 00:01:31,943
Notice all of the actual readings from three different satellites: the green, red, and blue lines.

26
00:01:31,968 --> 00:01:37,371
The actual data is much lower than any of the 102 models predicted,

27
00:01:37,396 --> 00:01:40,776
even though CO2 levels went up. There’s a fail.

28
00:01:40,800 --> 00:01:45,109
No kidding. The models are simply wrong.

29
00:01:45,134 --> 00:01:46,055
But wait,

30
00:01:46,080 --> 00:01:48,784
There’s more prediction failures.

31
00:01:48,809 --> 00:01:52,019
Model predictions for ocean temperatures were also wrong.

32
00:01:52,044 --> 00:01:58,059
This graph shows the models in red compared to the actual data from over 3,000 robotic instruments

33
00:01:58,084 --> 00:02:02,275
floating all over the oceans, from 2004 to 2012.

34
00:02:02,300 --> 00:02:03,935
Another fail.

35
00:02:03,960 --> 00:02:07,073
If positive feedback occurs from increased water vapor

36
00:02:07,098 --> 00:02:10,854
there should be an atmospheric hot spot in the middle lattitudes at the tropics.

37
00:02:10,879 --> 00:02:11,379
Okay.

38
00:02:11,386 --> 00:02:16,211
Again, note the models in red versus actual data from satellites and weather balloons.

39
00:02:16,236 --> 00:02:20,116
None of the data showed any hot spots. Fail again!

40
00:02:20,141 --> 00:02:21,823
I’m seeing a pattern here, right?

41
00:02:21,848 --> 00:02:23,209
Let’s keep going.

42
00:02:23,234 --> 00:02:27,998
Increased water vapor is supposed to trap more of the incoming solar radiation

43
00:02:28,023 --> 00:02:29,317
so more warming.

44
00:02:29,342 --> 00:02:34,481
As sea surface temperature rises there should be less outgoing radiation from the Earth

45
00:02:34,506 --> 00:02:38,095
but satellite measurements show outgoing radiation is increasing;

46
00:02:38,120 --> 00:02:40,663
the opposite of IPCC predictions.

47
00:02:40,688 --> 00:02:42,311
Yet another fail!

48
00:02:42,336 --> 00:02:44,983
The data shows positive feedback isn’t operating.

49
00:02:45,023 --> 00:02:45,604
No.

50
00:02:45,629 --> 00:02:48,731
In fact there is strong evidence for negative feedback

51
00:02:48,756 --> 00:02:53,282
probably resulting from enhanced cloud cover reflecting the sun’s radiation back into space.

52
00:02:53,307 --> 00:02:55,807
When negative feedback is taken into consideration

53
00:02:55,832 --> 00:03:01,353
the warming effect of doubling atmospheric CO2 is only about 0.5 degrees Celsius.

54
00:03:01,378 --> 00:03:04,668
Nowhere near the 4.5 degrees that some have predicted.

55
00:03:04,693 --> 00:03:11,076
Similarly a comprehensive study from a German company arrived at an ECS of 0.7 degrees

56
00:03:11,100 --> 00:03:15,529
and they also concluded that negative feedbacks more than offset positive feedback.

57
00:03:15,554 --> 00:03:16,911
So you know the bottom line here is:

58
00:03:16,936 --> 00:03:21,518
we don’t need drastic action to stay within the 1.5 degree target.

